04819nam a22005415i 9780774856256DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748562567 a10.59962/97807748562562doi  a(DE-B1597)662125  a(OCoLC)243614288  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.V3bC58 2000eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.1/2/021 aClayton, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIslands of Truth :bThe Imperial Fashioning of Vancouver Island /cDaniel Clayton. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b6 b&w illustrations, 8 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSpaces of European Exploration -- tIntroduction -- tCaptain Cook, the Enlightenment, and Symbolic Violence -- tSuccessful Intercourse Was Had with the Natives? -- tCaptain Cook and the Spaces of Contact at Nootka Sound -- tCook Books -- tHistories, Genealogies, and Spaces of the Other -- tGeographies of Capital -- tIntroduction -- tThe Conflictual Economy of Truth of the Maritime Fur Trade -- tNative Power and Commercial Contact at Nootka Sound -- tThe Spatial Politics of Exchange at Clayoquot Sound -- tRegional Geographies of Accommodation and Appropriation -- tCirculating Knowledge and Power -- tIntroduction -- tThe Ledger, the Map, and British Imperial Vision -- tCircumscribing Vancouver Island -- tDelineating the Oregon Territory -- tMythical Localities -- tConclusion: The Loss of Locality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Islands of Truth, Daniel Clayton examines a series of encounters with the Native peoples and territory of Vancouver Island in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Although he focuses on a particular region and period, Clayton also meditates on how representations of land and people, and studies of the past, serve and shape specific interests, and how the dawn of Native-Western contact in this part of the world might be studied 200 years later, in the light of ongoing struggles between Natives and non-Natives over land and cultural status. Between the 1770s and 1850s, the Native people of Vancouver Island were engaged by three sets of forces that were of general importance in the history of Western overseas expansion: the West's scientific exploration of the world in the Age of Enlightenment; capitalist practices of exchange; and the geopolitics of nation-state rivalry. Islands of Truth discusses these developments, the geographies they worked through, and the stories about land, identity, and empire stemming from this period that have shaped understanding of British Columbia's past and present. Clayton questions premises underlying much of present B.C. historical writing, arguing that international literature offers more fruitful ways of framing local historical experiences. Islands of Truth is a timely, provocative, and vital contribution to post-colonial studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peopleszBritish ColumbiazVancouver IslandxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485625640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774856256423Coveruhttps://www.degr